Getting Started
A Step-by-Step Guide to Using HCC Kubernetes Services
Note: Starting March 9, 2026, kubectl-anthos-config is no longer accepted. All users must use OIDC authentication to access clusters or namespaces. Please follow the step 3 below. To avoid access issues, ensure you run gcloud auth login at least once every 24 hours.
Prerequisites
Before you begin, ensure you meet the following requirements:
Cloud Native ID and GCP Group Membership
Determine whether you need Contributor Role access.
If you need to create a new namespace, request your manager or team lead to assign your MSID to the Contributor role within your team's resource group via the HCP console.
If you only need access to HCP console for information retrieval, the View-Only role will suffice.
Once you have either of these roles, visit HCP Kubernetes Console HCC Kubernetes Manage page to view the list of available namespaces. By clicking on a specific namespace link in HCC Namespace column, you can locate the GCP group under the "Console AD Group" field.
Namespace Access
If you require access to a specific namespace, add your Cloud Native ID to the corresponding GCP group.
Cloud Native ID
If you don’t have an active Cloud Native ID, follow the process outlined in "How to Create a Cloud Native ID" to create or activate one in Platform Azure (formatted as yourid@optumcloud.com), then join the necessary GCP group(s).
Service Account for CI/CD & GitHub Actions
The steps outlined above apply to individual IDs. If you need a service account for CI/CD or GitHub Actions, follow the instructions in "How to Create a Service Account."
Step 1: Create a HCC Kubernetes Namespace via HCP Console
Skip this step if your team already has a namespace.
Navigate to the Create Namespace Catalog in HCP Console Create Kubernetes Namespace
Alternatively, navigate from HCC Kubernetes Main Page and select Create Kubernetes Namespace.
Select a Resource Group Account:
Click Select a resource group and choose one to use.
Start the Process:
Click Start Now.
Provide Details:
PRM Resource Name: Example: <project/application_name>_<cluster_abbr(ctc/elr)>_<env_abbr(dev/test/stg/prd)>.
Toggle the checkbox to agree to the terms of service and platform limits.
Click Continue.
Configure Namespace Ownership:
Select the Cloud Native ID (namespace owner).
Toggle to Create new GCP group or choosing an existing using Select GCP group.
Click Continue.
Define Namespace Properties:
Kubernetes Namespace Name: Example: <project/application_name>_<cluster_abbr(ctc/elr)>_<env_abbr(dev/test/stg/prd)>.
Select Cluster: Based on application architecture.
For production, select peer cluster a geo-dispersed peer cluster will be presented. If a namespace with the same name exists in the peer cluster, map it by checking the box. Refer to application resiliency for more details.
Application Priority: Select P1/P2/P3 or lower. (updatable later)
ResourceQuota: Specify CPU (Cores) and Memory (Gi). This is to set an aggregate resource limit for this namespace.
Toggle Enable Logging (recommended).
Click Submit.
Step 2: Install Supporting Programs
Use Optum AppStore to ensure proper configuration (environment variables, certificates, etc.).
Windows Users
Submit a single request via AppStore for Google Cloud CLI 561.0.0.
This will:
Uninstall any older version of Google Cloud CLI
Install Python, gcloud, and kubectl
Configure required environment variables and CA certificates
Mac Users
Submit two separate requests via AppStore:
Python 3.14.2 (MAC) or later
Google Cloud CLI 561.0.0 (MAC)
Before submitting the Google Cloud CLI request, if gcloud was previously installed via Homebrew, run:
copy code snippet button
brew uninstall --cask gcloud-cli
The gcloud request will:
Remove any older version
Install gcloud, kubectl
Set up required environment variables and CA certificates
⚠️ Important Notes:
Do not run gcloud components update — it breaks the Optum customized installation.
For update, request newer Google cloud CLI version via AppStore.
Verify by running gcloud components list, a table should be listed.
Step 3: Download Cluster CA Certificates
Cluster CA Certificates are crucial to gain access to the cluster.
VDI users and those Windows users who don't have Developer_Elevated_Administrative membership:
Use this instruction link.
Choose the option "Automatically select the certificate store based on the type of certificate" and accept the import warnings for these self-signed certificates.
Windows users:
Download this PowerShell script windows_install_k8scerts.ps1
Locate that file and right click on it. Run it by clicking "show more options" and then "Run with Elevated Privileges (Audited)".
Explanation:
The above script creates a directory C:\Users\yourmsid\certs\k8s.
Downloads the certificates to this directory.
Imports those to Cert:\CurrentUser\Root, you will be prompted confirm import. Please accept that warning.
Output possible gcloud anthos auth commands for later use.
Mac users:
Run the following in a terminal.
copy code snippet button
TARGET_DIR="$HOME/certs/k8s"
mkdir -p "$TARGET_DIR"
cd "$TARGET_DIR"
for curfile in $(curl -s https://k8s.optum.com/certs/ | grep -o 'href="[^"]*crt"' | cut -d'"' -f2); do
  curl -O https://k8s.optum.com/certs/$curfile
done
ls -l "$TARGET_DIR" 
Explanation: The above commands create a folder, download cert files and overwrite if they exist. List the contents of the directory at end.
