4.3 Access namespace by use-context
List context
copy code snippet button
kubectl config get-contexts
Select a context to switch to, which is under the NAME column of previous command..
copy code snippet button
kubectl config use-context yourselectedcontext
# such as
kubectl config use-context elr-nonprd-usr101-elr-nonprd-usr101-default-cli-user
# finding the current context
kubectl config current-context
Note: This will only get you authorized to a cluster, not into a specific namespace.
Use kubectx and fzf you may improve your productivity to manage kubectl config context switch. It is available in brew in Mac or you may requestChocolatey for Windows. To install these productivity tool in mac or windows: run:
copy code snippet button
brew install kubectx
brew install fzf
copy code snippet button
choco install kubectx -y
choco install fzf -y
Once installed, run kubectx and you can start using arrow key or keystrokes to pick your context to switch to.
Step 5: Validate Configuration
Run:
copy code snippet button
kubectl -n yourk8s_namespace_name get sa
where yourk8s_namespace_name needs to be replaced by the namespace name you find in HCP Kubernetes Console HCC Kubernetes Manage page.
Expected Output:
copy code snippet button
NAME                        SECRETS   AGE
yourk8s_namespace_name      1         7d5h
❌ Troubleshooting:
Examine the test result error message closely to make sure you are using yourid@optumcloud.com id, not msid.
Retry the login command using yourid@optumcloud.com id again and authenticate via the browser prompt.
Deep Dive Troubleshooting:
follow https://k.goto.optum.com/debug , then open a brand new post in HCC Kubernetes teams channel.
!!! Note: If this step still fails, check to see if you have added your cloud native id in https://secure.uhc.com into the GCP Group found under the "Console AD Group" field. Refer to Prerequisites section on top of this page for more details.
